                 How Credit One Bank Stacks Up                                  
                     When it comes to APYs, Credit One Bank’s account offerings are top-of-the-line. But the bank falls short with its limited range of products and subpar customer support. 
 Credit One Bank vs. Capital One 
 Capital One  is also known for credit cards, and like Credit One, it offers several CDs and a high-yield savings account. However, the APYs on Capital One’s accounts fall slightly below Credit One’s offerings, with the Capital One Certificates of Deposit earning from 3.90% to 5.00% and the Capital One 360 Performance Savings Account earning 4.25% APY. 
 That said, both Capital One accounts have no minimum balance or opening deposit requirements, making them much more accessible than Credit One’s offerings. Plus, Capital One has a full portfolio of checking accounts and business banking products as well as a handful of physical branch locations scattered across the U.S. The hybrid bank also provides phone, chat, text and social media support. 
 Credit One Bank vs. American Express Bank 
 American Express , Member FDIC, is another online-only institution offering a host of popular credit cards as well as a high-yield savings account and CDs. Unlike Credit One, American Express Bank also offers a checking account and loans. 
 At 4.25% Annual Percentage Yield (APY), the rate on the American Express® High Yield Savings Account is competitive, though it doesn’t stack up to Credit One’s. The plus side is that you won’t need a minimum balance to open an account. Its CD rates are much more diverse, with competitive APYs for select terms and subpar APYs for others. 
 One area where American Express thrives, however, is in customer service. Among major credit card issuers, American Express consistently ranks in the top spot of J.D. Power’s Credit Card Satisfaction Study, while Credit One ranks at the bottom. 
 Credit One Bank vs. Marcus by Goldman Sachs 
 If you’re looking for an online bank with competitive interest rates, you’ll likely also come across  Marcus by Goldman Sachs . This relatively new institution offers a high-yield savings account, CDs, personal loans and a few credit card products. 
 In terms of competing with Credit One’s APYs, Marcus comes close, offering 4.40% APY on all balances, up to maximum balance limits on Marcus by Goldman Sachs High-Yield Online Savings Account no minimum balance requirement. The Marcus by Goldman Sachs High-Yield Certificates of Deposit offers rates from 3.90% to 5.10% APY, and the bank also offers a bump-rate CD. All CDs require a minimum deposit of just $500. 
 Overall, Marcus offers many of the same products as Credit One with slightly lower rates but much lower minimums. 



